- Assess all residents who meet the following Candida auris (C. auris) risk criteria:
- Have had recent surgeries;
- Are diabetic;
- Use broad-spectrum antibiotics and antifungals;
- Have invasive medical devices such as breathing tubes, feeding tubes, and central venous catheters; and/or
- Have frequent stays in health care settings (i.e., particularly in long-term acute care hospitals, and long-term care homes that provide ventilator care).### Precautions- If it is determined that a resident may have a C. auris-related infection:
- Notify the Infection Control Professional/Designate. - Implement Contact Precautions. - Reinforce with care staff the need for adherence to hand hygiene and the use of personal protective equipment (PPE). - Conduct appropriate lab testing per Physician/Nurse Practitioner direction. - Review the resident’s medication records and contact Physician/Nurse Practitioner for further direction if the resident has recently been started on antibiotics. - Ensure twice-daily cleaning/disinfecting for resident rooms with suspected/confirmed C. auris with an appropriate chemical.----**Helping People**
This document is uncontrolled when printed.
